        "text": "I\u2019m exploring a new venture at the intersection of content provenance, fingerprinting, and AI usage attribution (audio initially, potentially expanding to voice, animation, and other media).\nThe problem we\u2019re evaluating is how to reliably attribute creative works when they are used, transformed, or learned by AI systems not enforcement or takedowns, but provable attribution and auditability that could later support licensing or royalties.\nBefore building anything, we want to have a deep technical conversation with someone who has hands-on experience in areas like:\n\u2022 Audio or media fingerprinting / perceptual hashing\n\u2022 Robust similarity detection under transformations (compression, pitch/tempo changes, partial usage, synthesis)\n\u2022 Watermarking vs fingerprinting tradeoffs\n\u2022 False positives / false negatives in real-world systems\n\u2022 What is actually feasible vs academic or marketing claims\nThis is not a job post (yet). We\u2019re looking for paid consulting or advisory conversations to sanity-check an MVP approach before we pitch a pilot to talent agencies or studios.\nIf you\u2019ve worked on fingerprinting systems (music, video, speech, ML training detection, etc.) and are open to a conversation, I\u2019d love to hear from you feel free to email me @ dmschultz1964@gmail.com\nThanks in advance.",
